<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 6 GB MP3 Player Dark Blue
<Title>A little quirky sometimes but sounds great
<Date>Sat Dec 02 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>I bought this to use mainly with the Rhapsody subscription service and my own private collection.  MP3s and WMAs that I ripped from my own collection are easy to load and play great.  I have had several instances of the player not being able to find the licences to play the Rhapsody tracks.  Once the license expires (after a month or so) you have to delete the tracks and reload them.  The other thing is that the time and date on the Zen have to exactly match the time and date on the computer your are downloading from or the files will not play.  I took a while to figure this one out.  Some how the time has gotten changed on the Zen a few times without me realizing it. I don't know if I let the battery get too low or if it was caused by removing the battery or what but from now on when the files will not play the time and date are the first things I will check.   I used the Zen almost exclusivly in my two cars to play through the aux inputs and the sound is incredible.  The reasons for 4 stars instead of 5 are the synchronization problems stated above and the control panel - when you are sitting still it's pretty easy to navigate but it is almost impossible to do while driving (and you thought cell phones were dangerous!)  That brings up a cool feature of this player - the data storage funcion.  I have set up a portion of the players hard drive to act as data storage which I loaded with mp3s.  On of my Kenwood head units has a USB input which I plug the Zen into and I can then control the music through the head unit.  You could also use this feature to transfer large files between computers. As a side note, I've been using the Zen for about nine months and I have yet to have a problem with the headphone jack.  
