<Review ID>5334599
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 6 GB MP3 Player Dark Blue
<Title>What's an iPod?
<Date>Fri Oct 20 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>I've owned this mp3 player for over a year and have used it almost daily.  I have to admit, in terms of price, this is the best hard-drive mp3 player you could get for your money.  Sure, iPods have more eye-candy and if you like iTunes, then an iPod is probably the way to go.  However, if you use regular mp3 files and wma files, then I highly recommend this.  The sound is excellent.  With an equalizer and great volume controls, you won't be disappointed with the quality of the sound.  The one thing you have to get rid of, however, is the ear buds.  Don't blame Creative though, I've never seen a company issue high-quality or even decent quality ear buds with their mp3 players.    I also think that the handling of this mp3 player is much easier and faster than an iPod.  You can set the speed and sensitivity of the touchpad, so anyone can configure it according to his or her needs.  It doesn't take a long time to get used to and it's very easy to use once you get the hang of it.  I prefer it over iPod's wheel-style controls anyday.    The space is perfect.  For most of us, it wouldn't make sense to get a huge capacity mp3 player because of this reason: technology gets old.  By the time a few years pass, that $300, 80 gigabyte mp3 player you bought will be obsolete.  If you get this, however, it'll get old but at least you won't have spent a fortune.    Regarding the battery life: yes, the battery may seem to have a lot less life than advertised.  However, keep in mind that all companies follow this battery scheme.  Basically, the company loads a very large playlist and leaves the mp3 player on.  After a certain number of hours, the battery dies and the number of hours surpassed is recorded.  For most people, this is not exactly true.  For most of us, we have to fiddle with the volume, change songs, turn the player on/off, switch menus, etc.., which all drain battery life, especially with the backlight enabled.  So yes, theoretically, the battery could last 12 hours if under the best conditions.  Realistically, however, it's about half of that for most of us.   Finally, there are enough extras to keep anyone happy.  You could use this mp3 player as a USB flash drive(up to 4gb!), voice recorder, contact list, and even an alarm!    I absolutely love this mp3 player and when this one gets obsolete (it will) I'm going to buy another mp3 player from Creative.    
<Overall>5

