<Review ID>9003942
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 6 GB MP3 Player Dark Blue
<Title>Close but, half a cigar.
<Date>Wed Jan 04 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>I got this for Christmas and was pretty excited about using it right away. Unfortunately for me, I couldn't. A few things bothered me about it.  One of the top ones would be I couldn't connect or "sync" it to my computer.  I fiddled around with the thing for a day or so and then called Creative customer support(which by the way is not a free 800 number. I advise using a prepaid card or something.) I called as soon as the offices opened and was only waiting for about fifteen minutes. The tech support guy told me to go through various menus on the player and my computer and came to the conclusion that I needed to download windows service pack 2. With my dial-up connection it would take around 20 hours! So to put my music on it I have to have a friend with a high-speed connection save it to a flash drive first and then port it to my pc. Another draw back is that it can only charge with the supplied USB cable. There is no included charger as there is with the 5 gig model. Since I have a laptop computer, I couldn't get it to fully charge. I left it connected to my computer for over five hours and it's only supposed to take three. I have since tried again and switched the lock switch on while it charged and it worked. Full Charge! It does have an FM recorder though.  I've been able to record programming from an xm radio 2 go by transmitting music over it's FM transmitter and recording it on to the player. This will work ok for now until I get it going.     Negatives aside though, I love the player. It is extremely cool. The back of it is white, but it looks good with the dark blue at least in my opinion. It also has this cool little water drip graphic on the back. I haven't had a problem with the touch pad sensitivity at it's default setting at all.  The menus are pretty good too. You can customize them to display the things you want.The only thing that really bothered me was the fricken ear buds. They are BIG! They also have a little fuzzy covering on them that I found was great for pushing out your ear lobe and making the inside of your ear itchy. I took those off of the buds and that makes them a more comfortable fit. Problem now is they tend to fall out easier which isn't to big a deal. The sound quality on them is surprisingly good though. The player isn't super prone to scratches either. The back might be but you can't tell because it's white. I suppose you could squint really hard to find a scratch on the back but if you do that, frankly, you've got problems. The front of it won't get scratched because of the weird texture on the touchpad. The screen could but it won't easily like I've heard an IPOD does. I'm not going to name off all the features because that's in another review. So let me get straight to the point.   If you are looking for a cheaper alternative to the IPOD then this is it. The player is great and I love it. Even though I have been critical of the flaws, this device is a winner. The downside would be the crappy device to computer interface and the trouble getting started.  After that It's all gravy. If you do get it I suggest buying an AC adapter. I have not been able to find them at any retail store so far so save yourself the time and gas and just get it off of the Creative website. If you have trouble then don't waste anytime and call the creative helpline. I would definitely recomend over IPOD. Happy listening.  
<Overall>4

<Review ID>5328171
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 6 GB MP3 Player Dark Blue
<Title>Give it a month or two...
<Date>Fri Jan 06 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>I opened up my zen micro and I thought it was AMAZING.  It is small, light weight, cool touchpad, and I thought it was perfect.  I had read the reviews about how after a few months of use the headphone jack would kind of give out, and you would only be able to hear one frequency.  I thought that I would be careful enough, and this problem wouldn't happen to mine.  WRONG.  I was so careful with my player.  I had it in a case, I carried it carefully, I didn't put in my pockets, I never dropped it, etc.  5 months after having it, the headphone jack went bad, and now I have to jiggle it to find the perfect position so that I can hear.  Its not the headphones, I replaced those and still had the same problem.  Then a couple months after the headphone jack initially went bad, the player started acting really annoying. It would randomly turn on, and I would go to use it and the battery would be dead because it had been playing while I was away.  ANNOYING!  Then, it got so bad, that it would randomly turn on, I would turn it off, then it would turn on again, and so on.  Now, I have to take the battery out just to turn it off, and I keep it out until I'm ready to use it.  What a HASSLE.  I figured out that it has something to do with the headphone jack, which is right next to the on off switch.  I think inside the player, the headphone jack is rubbing up against the on off switch which causes it to turn on.  So, taking the headphones out of it when its not being used does help a little, but thats kind of annoying to have to do, and I think it losens the jack even more, which in turn, makes it worse when you want to listen to it.  This player also locks up every once in a while, which means you have to take the battery out, put it back in, and wait for it to do its thing and get back to normal.  You can definitely get a much better player for just a few bucks more, and I would definitely recommend doing so.  I wouldn't base your decision on the reviews by the people who just got their Zen Micro a few days ago, or even a few weeks ago, because as I said, its a pretty good player the first couple months.  Don't buy this player!  
<Overall>1

