<Review ID>4262899
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 6 GB MP3 Player Dark Blue
<Title>Zen Micro
<Date>Wed Sep 06 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>I have been disapointed in this player.  It was given as a gift eight months ago, and I am now returning it to the manufacturer for service.  A few days ago, the player froze mid-song and crashed.  I was unable to get it to reboot by either removing and then replacing the battery or using the website-recommended "reformat"/ "reboot" function.  Upon reading other reviews and talking with others who have owned this product, this is apparently a VERY common problem--one friend had the same thing happen with TWO consecutive products. Fortunately, I am still under the 1 year warranty period, and although the company wants to charge a minimum of $12.99 per customer service call, they do offer free email support.    Aside from this problem, the controls are awkward (the touch screen takes some getting used to, but it's bearable), and the playing options are frustrating.  For instance, the player does not allow you to shuffle all songs by a certain artist--you must navigate to that artist, then navigate to a particular album and are able to play only those songs.  The software does not support an option to view all tracks on the player without grouping them into individual artists/albums, so if you're looking for a particular song, you must navigate through the artist/album first.  Add to this, the battery life is also somewhat less than advertised.  Overall, this player is NOT to be recommended.  
<Overall>2

<Review ID>4272305
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 6 GB MP3 Player Dark Blue
<Title>Tried to buck the trend and paid the price...
<Date>Fri Sep 08 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>So I decided to be different and get a Zen rather than an Ipod.  I read the reviews, and was attracted to the replaceable battery, built in radio and extra storage space.  Certainly the Zen looks great on paper, then you get get one...   Let's start with ergonomics, the "touch pad" controls while having a gee wiz component are entirely impractical in the real world.  You cannot even graze the front of this thing without it stopping, fast-forwarding etc., so you have to lock the touch-pad to keep it in your pocket, holder etc.  Only problem there is you now have take it back out and unlock every time you actually DO want to fast forward etc.  Also, Creative does not make ANY gym/excercise holder for this model despite it being 3 years in production. Next is the operating system and software.  The Creative media source software is actually really good, it mirrors Apple's very closely, but here is the problem...Creative does not have an online music store, and the software will not work with ANY of the online stores to manage your song list, i.e., Windows Media Player, Itunes, Napster, etc. So unless you want to keep importing new downloads twice (once with whatever store, and then again into the Creative song list)the only solution is to install a new OS from Microsoft that works with Windows Media and Napster, but this new OS does not let you use the old software at all, and does not import your song lists, etc., also Windows Media player is terrible for managing this, it keeps re-importing songs you have removed and generates errors every time you synch.  So I finally reached my frustration point and got a new Ipod last week.  It just kicks the [...] out of the Zen players for the above reasons and also sound quality.  I am a musician so I think my ear is discerning. The Ipod has a built in EQ with 20 different sound modes, and the depth and detail of the sound is just well beyond what the Zen can produce.  
<Overall>3

