<Review ID>9535600
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 6 GB MP3 Player Dark Blue
<Title>It's okay.
<Date>Tue Aug 01 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>I got this MP3 in february this year. I had it for about 4 months until i decided to get an iPod video instead. While I had the zen micro the sound quality worked fine, i never experienced it skip once. The voice recorder and the radio were really nice features considering that you didn't have to buy them as extra accessories. The screen quality isn't that good though. The screen is rather small and the text is even smaller. And because the screen does not have any color it may be hard for some people to see the text. It is small and fits in your pocket easily. It is pretty thick but no very noticably. The real problem that I had was that somehow dirt and dust got under the plastic and infront of the screen it caused even more problems in seeing the text. I gave the zen to my mom and it works fine for her. If you are just going to be using it for working out and running this is probably a very wise choice, but if you are using it for casual use I would suggest the zen micro photo.   
<Overall>3

<Review ID>5747181
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 6 GB MP3 Player Dark Blue
<Title>Zen device OK, but the PC software is horrible
<Date>Tue Feb 07 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>Most reviews have focused on the Zen device, but don't forget you must synch up your music files from your PC with Creative Media Organizer software.  This is where Creative dropped the ball.  I first bought a 5GB Zen Micro, but that failed so I replaced it with a 6GB device.  It came with upgraded Media Organizer software, so I attempted to uninstall and install the software.  It works, but the program hangs and can't close unless I go into Windows Task Manager and kill the app.  I emailed Creative Support (email response time was not bad; received responses within 36 hours) and they provided me with a HIGHLY complex process to fully uninstall the software (get this: disable Starup Group via msconfig, re-boot in Safe Mode, set file directories to find hidden files....etc. etc. sheesh!!! Far too complex for the average user.  You can't just simply remove the software from the Control Panel!!!) and told me to try again.  I did and it got worse; the PC wouldn't shut down.  After much tinkering I'm stable, but it still hangs.  SO BEWARE: the software is clearly invasive and if you got it up and running don't touch it.  
<Overall>3

